asculine lens has distorted current medical understandings of menstruation, menopause, and childbirth, and has often led to faulty medical conclusions. Warsh also illuminates how the shift from informal to more formal, institutionalized treatment impacts both women's health care and women's roles as health practitioners. Always accessible and occasionally irreverent, Warsh's narrative provides readers with multiple foundations for reconsidering women's health and women's health care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Aug 2019) 0aFemmes - Soins medicaux - Etats-Unis - Histoire. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen's health serviceszCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen's health serviceszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / North America.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442686557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442686557.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG